segments.text: You had to use something that would get over the trees.
That was one of the things that we did every once in a while.
We didn't do it very long because somebody would figure it out and call the campus police.
That first year, did you go to any out-of-town football games?
We went to Baylor.
I think Baylor was an out-of-town.
How'd you get up there?
I went with one of my ball players, took us up there.
I had some friends at Baylor, so we looked them up.
from El Paso.
Did junior buddies ever hitchhike?
Never did.
My brother did.
That's about the time when it phases down.
Yeah, my brother hitchhiked a few times.
He never had a car in college, and I finally got one when I was a junior.
Right.
So that first year you got around by foot.
By foot.
Or by friend.
Or by friend.
Did your roommate have a car?
No.
So we both, me and both parents figured out we didn't need cars as freshmen.
Right.
How often did you communicate with your parents and how?
Every week.
Every Sunday night.
Call on my, you know, regular about 8 o'clock.
Make sure that, you know, my dad just said, all I want to hear is your voice.
I want to make sure you're still breathing and, you know.
And as you think back, how accurate were your descriptions of how things were going?
Oh, I made it pitiful.
I, you know, there, you know, I, of course, I poo-pooed it, made them, and the same with my letters and everything else.
I mean, I'm, to this day, my wife to this day doesn't believe I graduated from Texas A&M.
She says, you can't write.
I know you can't read.
So how did you get out of the school?
I said, well, I worked, you know, I did the work that was required.
Now you already had this special young lady back home.
Yes.
How did you communicate with her?
I wrote her letters and then I called her every week.
We could only talk for like three minutes.
Did she write you letters?
Oh, yeah.
I got one or two a week.
Remember your box number?
Oh, no, I had a different one every single year.
And your box was at MSC or at Northgate?
Northgate.
At Northgate.
Yeah, every year it was Northgate.
And did you get much other mail except from her?
No.
I mean, that's what I'd go for, is just to get letters from her.
My parents would ride.
My mom would ride.
Now, was she in school back home?
She was at UTEP.
At UTEP, okay.
She was a year behind me, but she went to UTEP.
Did you have any dates?
Well, fortunately, my brother made a lot of friends in College Station.
One of them was Joe Desa.
I don't even remember, Joe Joe was a referee.
D-A-I-S-A.
And his wife was Wanda, and she was always in the plays.
But they had a daughter and a son.
And the daughter was a couple years behind me.
Of course, Louie, my brother, was always trying
tell her hey now my brother's coming, my brother's coming, you need to get hooked up with him, all this kind of stuff.
And actually I wanted to play football at A&M and Gene Stallings looked at my tapes and I broke my neck when I was a senior.
So that went out the window but I was basically brought into College Station knowing the Daces and Bill Broach, I don't know, Bill Broach who owned the Shells?
There was a real good friend of mine.
And so my junior, my sophomore year, I never ate one meal at Sebesa Hall at night.
I'd walk over to the Deysa's.
They had a place for me every night.
Where did they live?
You remember where Tom lived?
Right behind the Presbyterian Church, that little subdivision over there.
At Northgate?
Northgate.
Right around in there.
They had a high house and I could walk over there and eat dinner and talk with Joe about it.
Because he was a basketball referee for the Southwest Conference.
And he stayed with my parents when he'd referee out there.
So he wanted me to be there every day to talk about sports.
Because his son was not interested in sports and his daughter wasn't interested in sports.
So we'd go over there.
And of course I got his daughter a date with Dave Elmendorf.
And they dated for two years.
So it was kind of a fun deal.
Having them there in town was like having family and they took care of me real well.
When did you go home for the first time that first fall?
I got to go home at Thanksgiving and at Christmas.
How did you get back and forth?
Airplane.
And what were, when you got home Thanksgiving, what did you tell your parents it was like?
How were things going?
Well, it was kind of unique.
My first, at Thanksgiving, I met up with a girl from Baylor who was one of my, you know, good, good friends in high school.
And she was cute as can be.
And I have a, I get off the airplane and my girlfriend's at the bottom of the, you know, you didn't have a,
walkway, you got off stairs.

You walk down this stairs and she's sitting down there at the bottom and I've got my arm around this girl with a cowboy hat on and my coat bag hanging over my shoulder and I'm walking off and she sees me and she's, you know,
That's how I got off the airplane the first time.
And I'm here explaining to her, this is so-and-so.
She's from Baylor.
I was just helping her out down the stairs.
So she proceeds to tell my mom that when I got off the airplane, I had my arm around this blonde, and I had a cowboy.
She'd never seen me in a cowboy hat.
I bought a cowboy hat down there.
So my dad thought it was the fun.
He thought that was the greatest thing in the world for me to get off the plane with a cowboy hat and an arm around this blonde.
We had a good time, and of course my dad saw me, and he says, holy cow, what have you been eating?
I gained about 20 pounds, and I think most of that was attributed to the beer.
And he says, is that what I'm paying for?
I told him, I said, you don't realize how much this costs.
This education has cost him.
That's the way the whole trip went.

the gaining weight and arms around girls and obviously you know you're doing okay you don't seem like you're you're you're struggling much you're certain uh all right and uh what what did you when they ask you what's it like how are things going what did you tell them i loved it i told them you know i said i'm never going to come back to el paso he says i'm going to live and
in East Texas, and I told my girlfriend that.
I said, you know, we're going to live in East Texas.
I do not ever want to come back to El Paso.
I love the humidity.
I love the rain.
I love everything about, you know, and most people hate it.
I mean, you tell them, and I loved it.
I acclimated to the humidity in a minute.
You know, I enjoyed it.
I enjoyed the green trees and all the stuff down there.
So being from the desert southwest,
They just couldn't understand it.
My parents, my dad especially, he, you know, because he came from Pennsylvania, he swore he'd never go through another wet winter, so.
What did you tell him about being an Aggie?
Of course, my dad says, well, how are you doing?
There's no women down there.
And my grandfather was very upset that I wasn't in the Corps.
Very, very upset.
He forced my brother to be in the Corps for three years.
Of course, my brother hated it.
And he literally would not talk to me about it, not because I wasn't in the Corps.
He says, you're missing everything.
And I said, my life is full.
I can't do anymore.
I said, I'm really pretty full.
But they wanted to know how architecture was going.
Because of course, my dad was, I want you to draw these set of plans for a new building we're going to build.
And they're all looking for.
They want that degree and that knowledge, and they want to start using it.
And so we did a project for him when I was third year with Larry, and we drew up a building for him and everything.
Then when you go home, Chris, let's say, no, the semester's not over in those days.
Finals.
How did that first semester go academically?
Well, see, we were on a three-point system when I first started.
So it was a struggle.
I got through the first semester was really I got through everything.
I passed everything pretty well, C's and B's.
I think I got a C in history and I think I got a C in English.
No, I failed English my freshman year, first semester.
Took it again in the spring and passed it.
But that first semester, I could not do the English.
I mean, it was a lot of reading and I'm not a reader.
All right, in hindsight, had Austin not done a good job in preparing you?
Not at all.
Is that right?
Not at all.

They did real well in the math, but because I think I didn't have parents that, as long as I was making B's and C's in high school, for me they thought, hey, for Sam, my brothers were all honor students, both above me and behind me.
I was the one in the middle that, you know,
If he can just get out and get by, we're going to let him slide.
So that's really how I got by with just about all of my education is just enough to get by.
All right.
So at the end of the first semester there was no break then.
Right.
You stay there.
And was Buddy Denton yet, was he still advising or had he already gone?
Yes.
No, I did meet him.
His name is really familiar.
I have coffee with him twice a month.
A group of old guys.
Barney Welch, one of the former football coaches, and oh, the head of the P.E.
department then.
Austin, no, Austin Curley, he's another one that joins us.
Oh, boy, my brain forgetting, too.
When you and your buddies went to class, how did you all dress?
Just Levi's and a shirt.
That was our daily.
And what did you take?
What kind of stuff did you take to class?
I always had a briefcase because I always had triangles and drawing stuff and compasses and everything.
So, you know, I thought I was a real nerd here.
Everybody else is just grabbing their books and walking to class, and I've got a briefcase, and I've got
Of course, I got three classes worth of stuff in there, so it was.
And so you're taking 18, 19 hours?
Yeah, I was taking 18 hours pretty much every semester.
One of the things that will probably dumbfound you, today the average student thinks 12 is full-time.
Well, our son was just graduated there.
Oh, okay.
All right.
And he was in the Corps.
He, you know, to digress, he fortunately got the full benefit of A&M.
He would consider me to be a two percenter.
And I'll have to say I was because, you know, all I did was go to architecture and go to work.
That was my life after baseball.
There was no other, you know.
That spring, as varsity, as baseball goes, was there a freshman team then?
There was a freshman team.
I played on the freshman team.
And what position did you play?
I was a pitcher.
Right.
And who were some of the other key freshmen that year?
Well, John Woods, Denny Beal, Charlie Jenkins.
R.J. Englert was a freshman with me.
R.J. went to the, he played on the A team or the varsity.
He played there.
About how many of those freshman baseball players thought they were going to play pro ball?
Not too many.
R.J. did.
Charlie did.
I think that was about it.
Everybody else was just there to play, you know, get through school.
And of the freshman baseball players that year, about how many of them were on scholarship?
I think it was four.
Four out of 15?
Maybe we had 15 on the team.
Now, did you describe, identify yourself as a walk-on?
Did you all use that term?
Oh, yeah.
You used that term?
That's what we did.
To me it was different because I was known as Lou's little brother.
Sure.
So, you know, and everybody says, well, you're not as good as your brother.
I said, well, there aren't too many that are.
So you've got to understand, you know, I said he was all Southwest Conference when he was a freshman.
He was a sophomore of the year as a sophomore.
All-American as a junior.
Very few ballplayers as good as my brother.
So I was always known as Lou's little brother.
You know, I really was not that good.
I shouldn't have, you know, I pitched a few innings and that's about it.
I was entertainment for Tom Chandler.
He'd put me at third base, because my brother used to play third base and he'd talk Spanish the whole practice.
And Tom would, it was hilarious because Louie would do a whole game in Spanish, a commentary in Spanish of what Chandler was doing and everything else.
I mean him and Tom were very, very good friends.
So here he puts me at third base and wants me to take infield.
And I can't catch nothing.
I'm telling you, I won't catch anything.
I wasn't going to get hit in the face with the baseball.
And he says, I don't care if you catch anything, just talk Spanish.
Tell us what's going on in Spanish.
I'd commentate the game in Spanish.
And every time I'd walk on the baseball field, all the guys that had played baseball would move out to this.
I'd walk on the field and he'd say, holy cow, when's the balloon going up?
Because I was gaining weight.
And by my sophomore year, he says, if you're going to pitch, you need to get about 20 pounds off.
I said, I'll get it off, coach.
I'll get it off.
And I worked diligently.
I got the weight off.
And I showed up in spring.
And he says, I thought you were going to get 20 pounds off.
He says, we need to work on this.
Every night, he'd be running me.
to get the weight off.
With spring baseball, describe the workouts.
I've watched college baseball now.
If the starters had 10 swings at the bat, that was a lot.
If they took 15 balls at infield, that was a lot.
Of course, our field was not Taj Mahal back there.

Tom had one assistant and it was it was a basically a very simple we didn't get much we didn't get much workout and with Tom not being able you know having a lot of help we didn't get much coaching I mean the key guys got the coaching I mean he'd concentrate on three or four guys five guys and work with them but I pitched a lot of batting practice
And I did a lot of running.
Now the varsity had about 15, 18?
18 people on it.
Okay.
And then you freshmen.
Workouts began about what time?
We'd get there about 2, we'd want to start about 3.
And it would go on how long?
Until 6 o'clock.
Did you all do any physical workouts?
We, yeah, we very limited weight lifting.
Back then weight lifting was not
you know, encouraged by baseball players.
For baseball players, they thought it'd make us, you know, hurt our muscles and we needed to be loose.
So we went to the workout room, but I mean, we never were allowed to weigh or lift more than so many pounds and that kind of stuff.
And where was that room?
It was right behind G. Raleigh.
Not G. Raleigh.
It was in the swimming complex.
Oh, oh, oh.
Down.
It was a dungeon.
Down's not a, the Down's an auditorium?
Or the old basketball arena.
Well, it was where the indoor swimming pool was.
Okay, all right.
It was right behind there.
And it was not, I don't know how anybody worked down there, but that's what we did.
Now, what equipment did the institution provide?
Did you have your own gloves?
We brought our own gloves and cleats.
They gave us a hat.
We got to keep our hats.
Everything else was uniform that we turned back.
So you got a uniform, they wash it for you, and they give it back at the end of the year.
Did you get assigned a number as a freshman?
Yeah, I got signed, I think it was 27.
It had no significance.
No significance.
Well, I got what was on it and what was there.
Did the freshman team play games?
Yeah.
We played about, I guess about 11, 12 games.
We actually traveled once.
With whom?
We played SMU, TCU, people in Southwest Conference.
We played Glenn and a couple other junior colleges.
And out-of-town games, where did you travel to?
We went to Austin one time.
Did you?
Well, that was our out-of-town game that year.
And did you all win it?
No, we didn't.
Oh, boy.
We didn't win too many against Texas when we played.
All right.
You worked out five days a week or six as a freshman?
Five.
Five.
Actually four.
Chandler figured Friday was like everybody else.
Everybody was going to go home.
So Friday we weren't really required to be there.
And you went to, you freshmen went to the varsity games but did not suit up.
Correct.
Did you all have any duties?
Oh yeah.
We raked the field.
We lined the field.
Whatever it took to get the field ready, that's what we did.
Did you all ever do any pranks, good bull?
I didn't.
class did.
I mean I got out of there before I was in varsity where all the pranksters were so I really didn't get to do much.
And you freshmen didn't do anything with the, you didn't play any, attempt any tricks on the varsity?
No, we were too scared of the varsity.
Those guys were all, you know.
Then spring break did you go home?
Of course that was just an Easter break then.
Yeah, but we didn't go home because we were playing baseball.
So we had to stay there.
About how many people attended the baseball games then?
Eh, if we had 50, it was a lot.
We thought we had a good crowd.
And the stadium, the baseball stadium was due south of the, of Kyle Field?
It was, yeah, southwest.
It was on that corner.
The center field was on the corner of G Rowley.
Yeah, that's what I thought.
I mean of Kyle.
Kyle, yeah, yeah.
Let's see.
You get your grades in the spring semester and how was that semester?
About the same.
I have to take English again.
I have to take the second semester English in summer school, which I took at UTEP.
Okay.
And you go back home and work for your dad.
All summer and then get ready to go.
I can't wait to get back to school.
And you're driving the truck and all that.
Yeah.
Did you ever think about transferring?
No.
Did you think about changing your major?
No.
I had, for some reason, I had the confidence, stupid as it was for not studying as much as I did, that I was just going to make it.
I mean, I was going to do whatever it took and going to summer school and working and just communicating.
I did a lot of talking to the profs.
I mean, I spent a lot of time in their offices.
Who were some of those?
I wish I could remember.
I had a woman English prof.
and I can't remember her name, but she, you know, I'd miss a lot of classes with baseball, and I went in there and said, I'm a baseball player.
You tell me what I can do to get a C in this class, and I'll do whatever you tell me to do.
I said, and I'm also an architecture student, so all my mornings are filled with

labs and I said so if it means coming in at night if it means doing whatever and she says no no but you know you're a horrible writer you can't write a sentence to save your life I said well I you know I'm very simple I'm a simple person I just simple sentences yes you are so she helped and she you know she gave me gave me a lot of credit on stuff that I did that you know that I could do so that's how I really got through my one of my English classes
And with Larry Priesmeier.
I mean, spending a lot of time in his, you know, other classes of his to just try and learn, you know, what I needed to do to get through the architecture.
I never struggled with architecture.
I struggled with everything else.
Allen Stasel, Rodney Hill.
Rodney Hill.
See, Rodney Hill was, you know, he was landscape.
And he was one of the guys that said he thought I would do better in landscape.
I said, are you kidding?
I don't want to.
And believe it or not, I was.
I had a landscape company for two years, putting in all those stupid plants that he was telling me the name.
So, you know, it comes back to bite you.
You know, the stories go, learn all you can because you may need it someday.
John Greer?
John Greer was there.
I still can't remember the guy that was from Santa Fe, Pecos, New Mexico.
Were there any, do you remember any famous people that came to lecture, to visit?
I don't.
We had, I.M.
Pei came to, he did a judging of some stuff that the upperclassmen did once, and then Phillip Johnson came.
Franklin Wright was still alive, I believe, but we saw a lot of his stuff.
How much did you and during those four years, how much did you and your buddies see of Romanek?
How visible was he?
A lot.
He was in every class.
I think he came by the class at least once or twice a week.
Make believe I didn't know him and as a close friend, describe Romanek.
Make believe I'd never seen him or heard him.
I'd describe him as a foreigner.
Because he was foreign to everything at that school except the architecture department.
I mean, he really was.
He drove a big black Buick Riviera.
And he'd park it right where nobody could get in and nobody could get out.
And he'd walk in.
And he'd walk in your class.
And he'd tell you, what are you doing?
I mean, to everybody.
I don't understand.
I don't understand.
What is this?
And he'd make you go through your diatribe on all this

know you try and make up some big thing about you doing he says it just looks like a pile of crap to me you know and and he'd walk out he wouldn't give you an explanation he wouldn't give you his theory and but he was very very knowledgeable and he was i think his his knowledge of the profession and where it was going and what it needed to what needed to happen in it was uh
very far reaching.
What was his purpose, you think, in those, in that routine, those questions?
I think he wanted to get us to think about actually what we were doing instead of just doing it.

I think he had been around long enough that he could take, you know, he could tell the BS and the people who were really thinking about their work and he could see, you know, he, I mean, we had some really brilliant kids, I mean, guys that I worked with in the architecture department, I mean, several of them got

fellows and they they went on i mean they were really pretty sharp guys and i i was just in awe of the things they could design and you know i didn't when you hear him come in and talk to these guys you think why can't i think like that you know why can't i do that you know you start you you just start seeing these are the architects that are going to be you know working for gerald heinz and working for the the people out there that are doing the things so it was you know it was uh
I always thought, what the heck is he doing in here?
I'm trying to do my work, and he's in here.
And of course, Larry Priesmeier encouraged it.
He'd want him in there.
So all of them did.
He would walk around, and I think he inspired a lot of people.
He certainly didn't inspire me, but he did inspire a lot of the people who were really true good architects.
All right, now he was the dean.
He was the dean.
Do you remember any of the other campus administrators?
Did you have any impression of Earl Rudder?
I thought, I thought Earl Runner did the greatest thing in the world.
He allowed women on campus.
I mean, that for us, that was, you know, you know, forget the Corps and all that stuff.
That was great.
You know, we weren't old army.
We thought, hey, man, let's do more things like this.
Let's.
If there had been a poll when you were an undergraduate by the A&M student body regarding the admission of women, what do you think it would have been?
Oh, 90% against and 10% for.
That's what I think.
I think because it was that the campus is still run by the Corps, and the Corps was not interested in having  I mean, talk about the students.
If you just took it out of the non-regs, then it would have been the other way around.
It would have been 90%.
But, you know, there was 13,000 guys there, and that's 6,000 of them were in the Corps, so
Describe the student body in general.
Where were they from?
What kinds of families?
What kind of background?
Income, geography, and so forth.
I say they're all middle class.
Very, very, very middle class.
All country folk, as far as I was concerned.
I mean, I went to Dallas with a few people.
But they're all real.
My brother came back and my dad says, oh, he's turned into a redneck.
I said, no, he's not turned into a redneck.
He's turned into a Texan.
We're from El Paso.
You've got to understand, El Paso mentality and Texan mentality are two different mentalities.
And my brother came back and he was just really, y'all.
It's just one of those things.
My roommate was from Nacogdoches.
bring two homemade cherry pies and his mom would show up and it was just like my mom.
She, you know, John would, you know, you got to clean your room, John.
You got to do this, John.
You know, my mom would, you know, when they came, that's the same thing.
And we had to clean up before they got there.
But the student body, was it diverse?
Were there some Hispanics?
Yeah.
I mean, one of the guys that plays in the band was from Mexico.
And a couple other guys on the baseball team were Hispanics.
So yeah, we had some Hispanics.
Of course, the Hill brothers were there.
On the football team, we had blacks.
And the Hill brothers were hilarious.
I mean, they'd come to baseball practice and go on the track.
And they'd try and hit the baseball.
They were rare characters.
Those two Hill brothers were pretty good guys.
As far as you know, how were Hispanics and blacks treated as A&M students?
I was Hispanic.
I mean, I let it be known, you know.
I mean, I spoke Spanish.
I did all that.
I don't have the skin color, but still, I never saw anything.
Everybody was treated the same.
Your struggle was getting through the school.
It wasn't against each other.
That's right.
You remember going to Silver Taps?
Yes, Silver Taps, Silver Taps.
I couldn't believe it.
Why are they doing this?
Did you and your buddies take it seriously?
Yeah, we did.
Everybody did, I think.
No jokes, no pranks?
No, it wasn't looked down on at all.
I was one of these guys, why are they doing this?
You kind of go, they're skeptical, and you go through it one time, and you think, oh, now I understand.
During your four years, four and a half years, was there ever a silver taps involving someone you knew well?
No.
Really, you know, because I was two years on campus and two and a half off,
I really can't remember anybody.
Now it's held every month and there may be three or four because student body being so much larger.
Religious activities, did you participate in any local religious group?
I used to go to the All Faith Chapel.
I went to church every Sunday.
I made it a prayer to walk and get to church and stuff.
I went to Catholic church.
But yeah, I tried.
You went over to St. Mary's?
Yeah, I tried.
And Sunday morning and Sunday night?
Just Sunday morning.
Sunday morning.
Were there a good many students that went?
Yeah, absolutely there were.
I mean, everybody would be walking, so everybody would show up.
And see, St. Mary's, it is doing well now.
They've got a big building over there.
It's really growing.
Religious emphasis week wasn't anymore, was it?
No.
See, in my early years there in the early 60's, there was a week in the spring and the YMCA was not an important place.
No, I never went to the Y.
Never did.
What about MSC?
Oh yeah, I went to MSC a lot.
What did you and your buddies do at the MSC?
Oh, just, you know, bold, hung around.
I spent most of my time at the Aggie Den.
At the where?
Aggie Den in Northgate.
It was a pool hall.
Oh, describe that.
It's equivalent, I guess, to the Dixie Chicken now.
They didn't serve alcohol.
It was just a pool hall and a bunch of girly magazines that you'd go in there.
And they probably was about half the size of the chicken.
Once a weekend you'd go over there and shoot some pool and talk to everybody and have a good time and just leave.
It didn't serve liquor.
I mean we, I can't remember if we were the, when they changed the drinking age to 18 or not.
It might have been because I remember we could start drinking and once we started drinking we generally.
Before that change, where did you and your buddies get drinks?
Did you all ever drive to Whiskey Bridge?
No.
I don't remember going down there.
Really?
Of course, for me it was kind of difficult.
I'd just go to the Daces and have a beer or two if I wanted to.
And I was never, you know, I never got drunk in college.
In Fowler Hall, did anybody keep any beer or stronger alcohol?
